instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "Life Cycle Stages: The DT lifecycle is captured through Model‑Based Systems Engineering (MBSE) and is structured into four abstraction layers. (1) Requirements: system needs are expressed in SysML requirement diagrams and use‑case models. (2) Functional Architecture: the functional structure is designed in SysML and linked to the requirements. (3) Logical Architecture: logical components and connectors are described with architecture description languages such as ACME, AADL and MontiArc, with behavioral extensions (e.g., MontiArc Automaton or SysML 1.7 state machines). (4) Product/Technical Layer: concrete components, connector specifications and implementation artefacts are produced in general‑purpose languages (C++/Java) and simulation tools (MathWorks Simulink or equivalent). Transitions between these stages are managed by mapping artifacts across abstraction layers – requirements trace to functional elements, functional elements trace to logical components, and logical components trace to technical implementation. Lifecycle governance is performed within the MBSE framework, ensuring consistency, traceability and coherent model updates."
]
